@scene goto_demo
title: Conditional Go-To
subtitle: The Crossroads
new-page: true

You stand at a crossroads. The path you take depends on your **Courage**.

This scene uses **conditional go-to** — the engine evaluates predicates and automatically routes you to the matching scene without player choice.

Courage is **[+ courage +]**.

- @goto_branch_start: Step forward (routed by courage)
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene goto_branch_start
title: Stepping Forward...
go-to: goto_branch_brave if courage >= 5; goto_branch_cautious if courage >= 3; goto_branch_timid

This scene has three conditional go-to targets. You should never see this text — it auto-routes immediately.

@scene goto_branch_brave
title: The Bold Path
subtitle: Courage 5+

Your high **Courage ([+ courage +])** leads you down the bold path without hesitation. The engine chose this route because your Courage is **5 or higher**.

This demonstrates `go-to: scene_a if courage >= 5; scene_b if courage >= 3; scene_c` — multiple conditional targets evaluated in order.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene goto_branch_cautious
title: The Measured Path
subtitle: Courage 3-4

Your moderate **Courage ([+ courage +])** leads you down a careful but steady path. The engine chose this because your Courage is **3-4** (the second predicate matched).

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene goto_branch_timid
title: The Careful Path
subtitle: Courage Below 3

Your low **Courage ([+ courage +])** steers you toward the safest route. This is the **fallback** — no predicate, so it matches when nothing else does.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene gotoref_demo
title: Go-To-Ref Demo
subtitle: Dynamic Navigation
on-arrival: destination = 0

**Go-to-ref** navigates to a scene whose ID is stored in a quality. Choose a destination, then the engine reads the quality value as a scene ID.

This is useful for dynamic routing — e.g. "return to wherever the player came from" or "go to the quest target".

(In this demo, we use regular choices since go-to-ref requires string quality values which our integer-based qualities approximate.)

- @gotoref_result_a: Set destination to "Result A" and go
- @gotoref_result_b: Set destination to "Result B" and go
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene gotoref_result_a
title: Destination A
subtitle: Go-To-Ref Target

You arrived at **Destination A**. In a full implementation, this would be reached via `go-to-ref: destination_quality` where the quality contains the scene ID string.

The **go-to-ref** feature is most useful when scenes need to remember and return to dynamic locations — like a "return from inventory" mechanic.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene gotoref_result_b
title: Destination B
subtitle: Go-To-Ref Target

You arrived at **Destination B**. A different dynamic destination.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene setroot_demo
title: The Camp
subtitle: Set-Root Demo
set-root: true
new-page: true

This scene has **set-root: true**. It is now the "root" scene — if any scene has no choices, a default "Continue..." button appears that leads back here.

The root is like a home base. Try going to the dead-end scene below.

- @setroot_deadend: Enter the Dead End (no choices inside!)
- @setroot_restore: Restore Hall as Root and Return
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene setroot_deadend
title: The Dead End
subtitle: No Choices Here

This scene has **no choices**. Because "The Camp" was set as root, a "Continue..." button should appear automatically, taking you back there.

This is how DendryNexus handles scenes that would otherwise strand the player.

@scene setroot_restore
title: Restoring the Hall
set-root: true
go-to: feature_showcase

Restoring the Great Hall as the root scene...

@scene call_demo
title: Call Demo
subtitle: Run Another Scene's Actions
call: call_helper
on-display: silver = silver + 1

This scene uses **call: call_helper** — it runs the `call_helper` scene's on-arrival actions *in addition to* its own, without navigating there.

It also uses **on-display** to add 1 Silver each time the scene is displayed.

The call_helper scene adds +1 Wit silently. Combined with this scene's on-display silver bonus:

Wit: **[+ wit +]** | Silver: **[+ silver +]**

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene call_helper
title: Helper Scene (Never Visited Directly)
on-arrival: wit = wit + 1

This scene is never navigated to directly — it exists only to be `call`ed by other scenes, contributing its on-arrival actions.

- @feature_showcase: (You shouldn't see this)

@scene conditional_text_demo
title: Conditional Text
subtitle: Dynamic Content Rendering
new-page: true

This scene demonstrates **conditional text** using the `[? if condition : text ?]` syntax. The text below changes based on your current stats:

[? if wit >= 5 : Your **sharp wit** draws admiring glances from the skalds. ?]

[? if wit <= 2 : The skalds smirk at your clumsy words. ?]

[? if courage >= 5 : Warriors nod with respect as you pass — they recognise a bold spirit. ?]

[? if courage <= 2 : You flinch at loud noises. The warriors pretend not to notice. ?]

[? if silver >= 8 : Your heavy purse clinks with every step. Merchants flock to your side. ?]

[? if silver <= 1 : You count your last coins and wonder where the next meal comes from. ?]

[? if reputation >= 7 : *The hall falls quiet when you speak. Everyone knows your name.* ?]

[? if reputation <= 1 : *Nobody here knows you. You're just another face in the crowd.* ?]

These lines only appear when their conditions are met. Try changing your stats and returning to see different text.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene unavailable_demo
title: Unavailable Subtitle Demo
subtitle: Disabled Choice Messaging

This demonstrates **unavailable-subtitle** — custom text shown when a choice is disabled by `choose-if`.

- @unavailable_locked: Try the Locked Door
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene unavailable_locked
title: The Locked Door
choose-if: has_rune_stone >= 1
unavailable-subtitle: You need the Rune Stone to enter

Behind the door, ancient secrets await. But first, you need the key.

- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene difficulty_curve_demo
title: Custom Difficulty Curves
subtitle: Scaler & Increment Tuning
new-page: true

These cards demonstrate **difficulty-scaler** (for broad checks) and **difficulty-increment** (for narrow checks), which let you tune the difficulty curve per-card.

Default broad scaler is 0.6. Default narrow increment is 0.1.

- @diff_curve_easy_broad: Generous Broad Check (scaler 0.9)
- @diff_curve_harsh_broad: Harsh Broad Check (scaler 0.3)
- @diff_curve_easy_narrow: Forgiving Narrow Check (increment 0.2)
- @diff_curve_harsh_narrow: Punishing Narrow Check (increment 0.05)
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene diff_curve_easy_broad
title: Generous Broad Check
subtitle: Scaler 0.9 — Very Forgiving
check-quality: wit
broad-difficulty: 5
difficulty-scaler: 0.9
check-success-go-to: diff_curve_success
check-failure-go-to: diff_curve_failure

This broad check uses **difficulty-scaler: 0.9** (default 0.6). The higher scaler makes success much more likely. Formula: `success = scaler * (stat / difficulty)`.

Wit: **[+ wit +]** vs Difficulty **5** with scaler **0.9**.

@scene diff_curve_harsh_broad
title: Harsh Broad Check
subtitle: Scaler 0.3 — Very Punishing
check-quality: wit
broad-difficulty: 5
difficulty-scaler: 0.3
check-success-go-to: diff_curve_success
check-failure-go-to: diff_curve_failure

This broad check uses **difficulty-scaler: 0.3** (default 0.6). The lower scaler halves your chances. Same difficulty, much harder.

Wit: **[+ wit +]** vs Difficulty **5** with scaler **0.3**.

@scene diff_curve_easy_narrow
title: Forgiving Narrow Check
subtitle: Increment 0.2 — Wide Band
check-quality: courage
narrow-difficulty: 5
difficulty-increment: 0.2
check-success-go-to: diff_curve_success
check-failure-go-to: diff_curve_failure

This narrow check uses **difficulty-increment: 0.2** (default 0.1). Each point of stat above/below difficulty shifts success by 20% instead of 10%.

Courage: **[+ courage +]** vs Difficulty **5** with increment **0.2**.

@scene diff_curve_harsh_narrow
title: Punishing Narrow Check
subtitle: Increment 0.05 — Tight Band
check-quality: courage
narrow-difficulty: 5
difficulty-increment: 0.05
check-success-go-to: diff_curve_success
check-failure-go-to: diff_curve_failure

This narrow check uses **difficulty-increment: 0.05** (default 0.1). Each point of stat only shifts success by 5%, making the check nearly a coin flip regardless of stats.

Courage: **[+ courage +]** vs Difficulty **5** with increment **0.05**.

@scene diff_curve_success
title: Check Passed!
subtitle: Success

The check succeeded. The difficulty curve was in your favour.

- @difficulty_curve_demo: Try Another Curve
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase

@scene diff_curve_failure
title: Check Failed
subtitle: Failure

The check failed. The difficulty curve was against you.

- @difficulty_curve_demo: Try Another Curve
- @feature_showcase: Back to Showcase
